DaVinci Bi-modal integration: Mouse Postnatal Brain (spatial ARP-seq, RNA + ATAC)

Overview

This notebook runs a bi-modal integration workflow for spatial ARP-seq data using DaVinci. The analysis proceeds in three stages:

  1. Horizontal integration within RNA across sections (cross-section integration)
  2. Horizontal integration within ATAC across sections
  3. Vertical (cross-modality) integration between RNA and ATAC, followed by clustering, optional spatial refinement, and visualization

Setup

Load DaVinci and set the working directory.

library(DaVinci)
library(ggpubr)

setwd("~/For_Tutorial/ARP-seq/")

Part I Horizontal integration across sections (RNA)

Load RNA section files and preprocess

We read each RNA section from data.dir/RNA/. Each RDS file is expected to contain: - mat: feature-by-spot raw counts matrix - coor: spot-by-(x,y) coordinates

We preprocess each section with preprocess(..., type="rna", graph.opt="Tri.mesh") and collect: - Y.list: processed data matrix per section - L.list: spatial graph/Laplacian per section - coor.list: aligned coordinates per section

data.dir <- "~/For_Tutorial/ARP-seq/data/"

dataset.opts <- list.files(paste0(data.dir, "RNA/"))
dataset.opts <- gsub(".RDS", "", dataset.opts)

Y.list <- list()
L.list <- list()
coor.list <- list()

for (ii in seq_along(dataset.opts)) {
  input <- readRDS(paste0(data.dir, "RNA/", dataset.opts[ii], ".RDS"))
  
  fin <- preprocess(
    input$mat,
    input$coor,
    type = "rna",
    graph.opt = "Tri.mesh",
    frac.thr = 0.95
  )
  
  Y.list[[ii]] <- fin$mat
  L.list[[ii]] <- fin$L
  coor.list[[ii]] <- fin$coor
}

names(coor.list) <- dataset.opts

Run RNA horizontal integration

Horizontal.Integration.Assemble() searches over a candidate list of latent dimensions (k.arg.list) and integrates robust latent variables across sections.

RNA.res <- Horizontal.Integration.Assemble(
  dataset.opts = dataset.opts,
  Y.list  = Y.list,
  L.list  = L.list,
  coor.list = coor.list,
  k.arg.list = c(4, 6, 8, 10, 11, 12, 13, 15, 16, 18, 20, 22, 24)
)

Part II Horizontal integration across sections (ATAC)

Load ATAC section files and preprocess

We repeat the same steps for ATAC. In the original script, type="rna" is used in preprocess() for ATAC matrices as well. If you have an ATAC-specific preprocessing pathway (e.g., LSI), you may want to switch to type="atac" and add LSI parameters. Here we keep the original behavior for fidelity.

dataset.opts <- list.files(paste0(data.dir, "ATAC/"))
dataset.opts <- gsub(".RDS", "", dataset.opts)

Y.list <- list()
L.list <- list()
coor.list <- list()

for (ii in seq_along(dataset.opts)) {
  input <- readRDS(paste0(data.dir, "ATAC/", dataset.opts[ii], ".RDS"))
  
  fin <- preprocess(
    input$mat,
    input$coor,
    type = "rna",
    graph.opt = "Tri.mesh",
    frac.thr = 0.95
  )
  
  Y.list[[ii]] <- fin$mat
  L.list[[ii]] <- fin$L
  coor.list[[ii]] <- fin$coor
}

names(coor.list) <- dataset.opts

Run ATAC horizontal integration

ATAC.res <- Horizontal.Integration.Assemble(
  dataset.opts = dataset.opts,
  Y.list  = Y.list,
  L.list  = L.list,
  coor.list = coor.list,
  k.arg.list = c(4, 6, 8, 10, 11, 12, 13, 15, 16, 18, 20, 22, 24)
)

Part III Vertical integration (RNA + ATAC), clustering, refinement, visualization

Align shared pixels between modalities

We take the integrated matrices from RNA and ATAC, assign unique row identifiers of the form <slice>@<pixel>, and then restrict both matrices to their intersection (pixels present in both modalities).

mat.RNA <- RNA.res$mat
mat.ATAC <- ATAC.res$mat

rownames(mat.RNA) <- paste0(RNA.res$mat.slice.id, "@", rownames(mat.RNA))
rownames(mat.ATAC) <- paste0(ATAC.res$mat.slice.id, "@", rownames(mat.ATAC))

sids.intersect <- intersect(rownames(mat.RNA), rownames(mat.ATAC))
mat.RNA <- mat.RNA[sids.intersect, ]
mat.ATAC <- mat.ATAC[sids.intersect, ]

sids <- rownames(mat.RNA)
mat.slice.id <- unlist(lapply(strsplit(sids, "@"), function(x) x[1]))
sids.pixel <- unlist(lapply(strsplit(sids, "@"), function(x) {x[2]}))

Run bi-modal integration and cluster

BiModalIntegration() builds a cross-modality neighbor graph, which we cluster using leiden_adaptive(). The resulting partition is a cluster label per pixel.

integration.res <- BiModalIntegration(
  modal.1 = mat.RNA,
  modal.2 = mat.ATAC,
  n_neighbors = 40,
  n_neighbors_large = 40,
  L2norm = "column"
)
## [1] "No adjustment with reference UMI."
partition <- leiden_adaptive(
  integration.res$snn.mat,
  num.of.cluster = 18,
  resolution.start = 0.4,
  adaptive.size = 2,
  method = "louvain"
)
## 1.6 0.8 1.6
## 1.2 0.8 1.6
## 1 0.8 1.2
## 1.1 1 1.2
partition <- as.character(partition)
names(partition) <- sids.pixel

Local smoothing / spatial refinement

We optionally refine cluster labels within each section using DaVinci:::refinement() with a KNN neighborhood.

Important: the coordinates used here must be aligned to the same pixel IDs used in names(partition). In this script, names(partition) are the pixel IDs without the slice prefix (e.g., the part after "@"). This matches the original code and assumes rownames(coor.list.<...>[[ii]]) are also pixel IDs (without slice prefixes).

partition.smooth <- partition


for (ii in seq_along(dataset.opts)) {
  subpart.index <- which(mat.slice.id == dataset.opts[ii])
  
  p.part <- partition[subpart.index]
  
  p.part <- DaVinci:::refinement(
    p.part,
    as.matrix(coor.list[[ii]])[names(p.part), ],
    neighbor.option = "KNN",
    neighbor.arg = 8,
    tasks = "discrete"
  )
  
  partition.smooth[subpart.index] <- p.part
}

Visualize clusters across sections

We define per-section orientation settings (named by section IDs) and then visualize cluster assignments with scatter.DiscretePlot.list().

orientation.opts <- c("yx", "yx", "y-x", "y-x", "-x-y")
names(orientation.opts) <- c("P0", "P2", "P5", "P10", "P21")

par.to_plot <- partition.smooth

plot.list <- scatter.DiscretePlot.list(
  par.to_plot,
  coor.list,
  mat.slice.id,
  dataset.opts,
  pt.size = 0.2,
  title.size = 30,
  orientation = orientation.opts,
  ratio = NULL,
  return.obj = TRUE
)

ggarrange(
  plotlist = plot.list[match(c("P0", "P2", "P5", "P10", "P21"), dataset.opts)],
  nrow = 1
)

Part IV Subclustering a selected cluster

Sometimes a cluster contains substructure. Here we subcluster the pixels assigned to cluster "14" using the same graph, restricted to those pixels.

par.to_plot <- partition.smooth
subcluster.index <- which(par.to_plot == "14")

ptm <- proc.time()
partition.sub <- leiden_adaptive(
  integration.res$snn.mat[subcluster.index, subcluster.index],
  num.of.cluster = 2,
  resolution.start = 0.4,
  adaptive.size = 2,
  method = "louvain"
)
print(proc.time() - ptm)
##    user  system elapsed 
##   0.311   0.000   0.311
par.update <- par.to_plot
par.update[subcluster.index] <- paste0("N", partition.sub)

# Manual relabeling based on domain knowledge:
# N0 is more dorsal
par.update[par.update == "N0"] <- "8"
par.update[par.update == "N1"] <- "13"

# Renumber to keep labels coherent (as in original script)
par.update[par.update == "15"] <- "14"
par.update[par.update == "16"] <- "15"
par.update[par.update == "17"] <- "16"

Visualize updated clusters (white-on-black background)

plot.list <- scatter.DiscretePlot.list(
  par.update,
  coor.list,
  mat.slice.id,
  dataset.opts,
  pt.size = 0.2,
  title.size = 30,
  orientation = orientation.opts,
  ratio = NULL,
  return.obj = TRUE
)

for (ii in seq_along(plot.list)) {
  plot.list[[ii]] <- plot.list[[ii]] +
    theme(
      plot.title = element_text(color = "white", hjust = 0.5),
      plot.background = element_rect(fill = "black"),
      legend.position = "none"
    )
}

ggarrange(
  plotlist = plot.list[match(c("P0", "P2", "P5", "P10", "P21"), dataset.opts)],
  nrow = 1
)
